      <hedline>
        <hl1>Auschwitz Today</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Eliezer M Rabinovich letter urges fellow Jews to be more tolerant of crosses near Auschwitz, where many Polish Catholics also died, and disco where young people can enjoy themselves; says Jews must not concentrate exclusively on the dead and not allow people to live normal lives (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It is good that the old synagogue near Auschwitz has been restored and reopened (news article, Sept. 13). But maybe we Jews should become more tolerant of the crosses nearby. Many Polish Catholics were also killed.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It is good that the old synagogue near Auschwitz has been restored and reopened (news article, Sept. 13). But maybe we Jews should become more tolerant of the crosses nearby. Many Polish Catholics were also killed.</p>
        <p>Also, regarding the disco that recently opened in the area, if Oswiecim (Auschwitz) were a ghost town, and dancers were exported by helicopter from Warsaw to insult the memory of those killed, the protests would be justified. But it is a town alive with young people, and they need a place for entertainment.</p>
        <p>Fifty-five years after the war we cannot concentrate exclusively on the dead (even dead as a result of a crime as enormous as the Holocaust) and not allow people to live normal lives.</p>
        <p>ELIEZER M. RABINOVICH  Berkeley Heights, N.J.  Sept. 13, 2000</p>
      </block>
